result.execSummary:
The defendant Christopher Monroe was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 1st Degree Child Sex Assault - Sexual Contact with Person under Age of 13, a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: In the Wisconsin State Prison System

superMiscConds.notes: If revoked, court costs, fees and surcharges be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.

supervisions.notes: Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Earned Release Program. Defendant is not appropriate for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

miscConds.notes:
No contact with the victim or victim's mother Anisha M. Court will allow therapeutic contact between Anisha M. and the defendant. Court will allow therapeutic contact between the victim and defendant with the consent of the victim's mother and the therapist.
Prohibited from maintaining any social media accounts. Defendant may have an email account. Any electronic devices with internet capabilities to be turned over to agent for inspection upon demand.
No unsupervised contact with any child under the age of 16 years. Defendant's wife may not be the supervising adult.

Provide DNA sample (unless previously submitted) and pay surcharge. Restitution set at ZERO. Pay all costs, fees and surcharges during period of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

Register and comply with the sex offender registry. Obtain/comply with sex offender treatment. Cooperate with psychological evaluation upon entering probation. Report make, model and license plate of vehicle to agent. Attend cognitive thinking class.
Continue educational program and maintain current employment.
Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession; Voting.

timeConds.notes: Forthwith. Huber privileges for classes at MATC, work release, and release for therapy sessions.

Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea. Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.
